\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Overview 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Objective
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimate the capitalization effect of local sewage spill exposure on house prices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key empirical challenge is that CSO spill behaviour is highly persistent.
 Some CSOs spill frequently and others rarely do,
 meaning most variation is cross-sectional.
 Houses near chronically bad CSOs are always cheaper.
 This makes it difficult to distinguish spill effects from unobserved neighbourhood quality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our strategy generates plausibly exogenous within-area,
 over-time variation in spill exposure using rainfall shocks and predetermined hydraulic constraints.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Identification Logic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strategy combines three components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Rainfall shocks (exogenous time variation)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Rainfall provides plausibly exogenous shocks to sewer systems.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
On its own,
 rainfall affects all areas,
 but it does not translate uniformly into spills.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Predetermined hydraulic constraints (supply-side heterogeneity).
 Whether rainfall causes spills depends on hydraulic stress:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Wastewater treatment works (WwTW) loading relative to design capacity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
CSO baseline hydraulic sensitivity.
 Or,
 elevation-based hydraulic slack within the interceptor system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
These constraints are predetermined by historical engineering design and long-run infrastructure capacity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Rainfall × hydraulic stress generates differential spill responses across systems.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
River-network exposure (demand-side mapping).
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Once a CSO spills,
 sewage enters the river network and travels downstream.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Exposure depends on:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Whether a house lies downstream of the CSO,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Distance along the river network,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Tidal conditions.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
We construct house-level spill exposure by aggregating CSO-level spills using downstream river-distance weights.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Empirical Implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 1:
 First Stage (CSO-level)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimate how rainfall shocks interacting with predetermined hydraulic stress affect CSO spill intensity,
 including CSO fixed effects and time fixed effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Identification comes from differential translation of rainfall into spills across systems with different hydraulic constraints —
 not from baseline spill levels.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align block

\series bold
Step 2:
 Exposure Mapping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Predicted CSO spills are aggregated to the house level using river-network connectivity weights.
 Only downstream exposure enters the baseline specification.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\series bold
Step 3:
 House Price Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* Log house price on recent downstream spill exposure,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* Controlling flexibly for rainfall in the same window,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* Including neighbourhood fixed effects and quarter-time fixed effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Identification comes from within-neighbourhood,
 within-time variation in spill exposure induced by rainfall × hydraulic constraints.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rainfall is controlled for directly,
 so the instrument operates only through the spill channel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Exclusion Restriction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conditional on neighbourhood fixed effects and rainfall controls:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* Hydraulic stress affects house prices only through CSO spill intensity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* It does not directly alter flood risk,
 schools,
 transport,
 or other amenities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* River-network exposure is mechanically determined by geography.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Alternative Instruments and Robustness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Alternative instruments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* Hydraulic slack (elevation gradient relative to WwTW),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* Soil permeability (geological runoff capacity),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* WwTW loading ratios.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are predetermined engineering or geological features and enter only through interaction with rainfall shocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Time Aggregation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Buyers may capitalize long-run spill expectations rather than single events.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We therefore examine:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* Short-run spill exposure windows (salience effects),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* Annual or rolling averages (long-run expectations).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Short-run windows provide sharper quasi-experimental variation;
 longer windows capture belief formation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Baseline 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We exploit exogenous rainfall shocks interacting with predetermined hydraulic constraints at the wastewater treatment works and CSO level to generate differential variation in spill intensity.
 House-level exposure varies mechanically according to downstream river connectivity.
 Within-neighbourhood,
 within-time variation in predicted spill exposure identifies the capitalization effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our identification combines (i) exogenous rainfall shocks,
 (ii) predetermined hydraulic constraints that govern how rainfall translates into CSO spills,
 and (iii) river-network connectivity that determines which houses are exposed once spills occur.
 The strategy proceeds in three steps:
 first,
 we estimate how rainfall interacting with hydraulic stress predicts CSO-level spill intensity;
 second,
 we map predicted spills to houses using downstream river connectivity;
 third,
 we estimate the capitalization of this predicted spill exposure in house prices within neighbourhood and time fixed effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rainfall shocks × predetermined hydraulic constraints → differential spill intensity → river-based house exposure → capitalization in house prices.
\end_layout

