\begin_layout Plain Layout
The logic of the instrument and controls is that the instrument shifts CSO spill intensity while the controls absorb the direct effects of the same underlying geography on house prices.
 The concern is that the CSO's elevation relative to the treatment works might correlate with the house's own elevation —
 both the CSO and nearby houses sit at similar elevations because they are in the same terrain.
 If high-elevation areas have higher house prices (views,
 lower flood risk),
 and high-elevation CSOs spill less,
 then CSO elevation would spuriously predict higher house prices even without any causal effect.
 Controlling directly for house elevation,
 the residual variation in CSO elevation —
 specifically,
 the elevation of the CSO relative to the treatment works within the same terrain zone —
 is no longer correlated with house prices through the terrain channel.
 What remains is the hydraulic channel:
 how much available gradient the CSO has.
 Formally,
 the instrument is not 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{c}$
\end_inset

 alone but contains 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{c}-z_{w}$
\end_inset

,
 the differential.
 This differential is what determines available gradient,
 and it varies across CSOs within the same terrain zone because treatment works are sited at specific,
 historically fixed locations that differ from the average elevation of each CSO's terrain.
 Conditional on controlling for the ground elevation of the property directly (
\begin_inset Formula $z_{h}$
\end_inset

 to control for flood risk,
 views,
 terrain effects on prices),
 its distance to the treatment works (
\begin_inset Formula $L_{hw}$
\end_inset

 to control for any treatment works proximity disamenity) and the catchment fixed effects (to control for all between-catchment variation),
 the available hydraulic gradient 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{cw}$
\end_inset

 is unlikely to have direct effects on modern house prices.
 
\end_layout

