\begin_layout Plain Layout
With transaction-level data,
 a repeat sales sample can be constructed to address neighbourhood quality confounding —
 houses that transact at least twice —
 and difference out the house fixed effect properly.
 The question is whether there is enough within-house variation in nearby spill intensity between the two sale dates to identify β.
 The panel is short so there need not be enough transactions and it would need the rainfall-driven variation in spills to be large relative to the persistent component.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
First,
 a cross-sectional hedonic using time-averaged spill rates per CSO,
 with rich neighbourhood controls and WwTW-time fixed effects,
 comparing houses across CSOs within the same catchment in the same year.
 This gives the full capitalisation effect but is still vulnerable to sorting bias.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Second,
 a first-differences or repeat-sales specification using changes in spill intensity between sale years,
 instrumented with changes in rainfall interacted with PE stress.
 This is clean but may have weak first stage if spills don't move much.
\end_layout

